03:01.849 --> 03:05.592
[ Saroyan ]
A neighbor spotted smoke
about 7:00 am.

03:05.686 --> 03:08.519
But it was a cold morning,
so he thought it was
just the fireplace.

03:08.606 --> 03:10.972
Then a little while later,
he saw flames,

03:11.067 --> 03:13.649
called 911, and the fire
was out by 10:00 am.

03:13.736 --> 03:15.442
Oh, God,
I hate the toasty ones.

03:15.529 --> 03:18.817
And I prefer them with heads.
Uh, careful. This guy’s pretty brittle.

03:18.908 --> 03:23.777
Judging by the oval shape
of the obturator foramen,
the victim is female.

03:23.871 --> 03:27.614
The granular appearance
of the pubic face
indicates mid—30s.

03:27.708 --> 03:29.790
Well, half the stuff in here
has been scorched or melted.

03:29.919 --> 03:32.911
Something in here
must have been valuable.
Workshop materials mostly.

03:33.005 --> 03:36.543
This is a partially melted wrench,
some bolts, screws.

03:36.634 --> 03:38.340
[Chuckles]
This was a drill.

03:38.427 --> 03:40.167
Ammunition all over the place.

03:40.262 --> 03:44.801
High explosives, bullet casings—
probably what caused
this place to go ablaze.

03:44.892 --> 03:47.884
But there’s only one gun—
the pistol she was holding.

03:47.978 --> 03:49.388
[ Booth ]
Maybe the others were stolen.

03:49.522 --> 03:52.730
I think that’s a gravity shower.
[ Booth ]
Maybe she was living here.

03:52.817 --> 03:56.480
— Or hiding out.
— She was decapitated
by the shelf.

03:56.612 --> 03:59.604
What?
Yeah, she must have been thrown
against the shelving...

03:59.698 --> 04:01.199
from a blast of some kind.

04:01.283 --> 04:04.025
That is the only way
there would be this much damage.

04:04.120 --> 04:05.781
Her head has to be
around here somewhere.

04:05.871 --> 04:07.907
[ Saroyan ]
We’re still searching
through the debris.

04:07.998 --> 04:10.614
- This vest never burned.
- Fire—resistant.

04:10.709 --> 04:14.076
— Maybe she was expecting this.
- What kind of person expects this?

04:14.171 --> 04:16.787
— Okay, Bones, cause of death.
— It’s too soon to give a definitive answer.

04:16.882 --> 04:19.669
- Why?
— Decapitation might
have played a part.

04:19.760 --> 04:21.261
That would certainly
factor in.

04:21.345 --> 04:24.837
Oh, found the head...
in the toilet.

04:28.144 --> 04:30.305
Okay, that’s a rough way
to be remembered.

05:15.065 --> 05:16.726
[ Daisy]
Oh, my God,
a gunshot wound.

05:16.817 --> 05:19.194
I guess the vest
wasn’t bulletproof.

05:20.154 --> 05:21.644
[ Brennan ]
There are two bullets.

05:21.739 --> 05:25.277
And I think you’ll find
that they’re joined.

05:25.367 --> 05:27.358
— By a wire.
— These are not legal.

05:27.453 --> 05:28.568
It’s called a bolo.

05:28.662 --> 05:30.653
Booth will know more.

05:30.748 --> 05:33.364
Dr. Brennan, may I ask
a personal question?

05:33.459 --> 05:35.370
Yes. But I may not answer.

05:36.587 --> 05:39.329
ls Lance finally moving out
ofyourhouse?

05:39.423 --> 05:40.924
He has stated his intention.

05:41.008 --> 05:44.171
He was only supposed to stay
with us until he found a place.

05:44.261 --> 05:45.592
He found one.

05:45.679 --> 05:47.294
Apparently, there are
two other psychologists...

05:47.389 --> 05:48.845
living in the building,

05:48.933 --> 05:51.094
so they can all pretend
to be scientists together.

05:51.227 --> 05:53.809
I’m sure you’ll be glad
to get your privacy back.
Yes.

05:53.896 --> 05:56.353
Except it is my impression...

05:56.440 --> 05:58.772
that Sweets is the only person
in the world...

05:58.859 --> 06:01.350
that Booth, Christine and I
like the same amount.

06:01.445 --> 06:03.936
Even though liking
is not quantifiable.

06:04.031 --> 06:07.364
Yes. And emotions
are unreliable.

06:07.451 --> 06:10.363
The distal phalanges were
too burned to be saved.

06:10.454 --> 06:12.695
The radius, ulna, thorax...

06:12.790 --> 06:15.202
and anterior plane
of the lower extremities...

06:15.292 --> 06:17.078
all calcined from the fire.

06:17.169 --> 06:20.127
The back, shoulders and buttocks
are dark to light gray,

06:20.214 --> 06:21.829
indicating less exposure.

06:21.966 --> 06:25.083
The vest was flame—retardant, or
else we’d have no flesh at all.
[ Device Beeps ]

06:25.177 --> 06:26.963
The property and the shed...

06:27.054 --> 06:29.966
belonged to a woman
named Deanna Barbieri.

06:30.057 --> 06:32.423
Single, ex—military.

06:34.103 --> 06:36.890
A veteran?
I hate when it’s a veteran.

06:36.981 --> 06:41.441
I got a recent set of her chest X—rays
from the VA from about a year ago.

06:41.527 --> 06:44.735
She came in suffering from
shortness of breath and a fever.

06:44.822 --> 06:47.734
Oh. A victim identification
from a chest X—ray?

06:47.825 --> 06:48.814
Is that possible?

06:48.909 --> 06:50.570
[ Brennan ]
From the size, shape...

06:50.661 --> 06:54.153
and position of the transverse
processes of the vertebrae,

06:54.248 --> 06:57.490
it appears that both X—rays
belong to the same person.

06:57.585 --> 07:00.702
But we can’t be certain certain,
just mostly certain.

07:00.796 --> 07:03.583
Certain is an absolute, Ms. Wick.
You can’t be mostly certain.

07:03.674 --> 07:05.505
Mostly certain is good for me.

07:05.593 --> 07:08.335
From the angle
of the entry wound,

07:08.429 --> 07:13.139
the slugs would have
most likely transected
the inferior vena cava.

07:13.225 --> 07:15.261
Cause of death.
Thank you.

07:15.352 --> 07:18.765
— Tied with decapitation.
- Uh, Ms. Wick is right.

07:18.856 --> 07:21.973
But we can’t be sure
if the victim was still alive...

07:22.067 --> 07:24.604
at the moment her head
was separated from her body.

07:24.695 --> 07:26.981
— [ Saroyan ] Vena cava’s
good enough for me!
— [Cell Phone Rings]

07:27.072 --> 07:29.108
- [ Beeps]
- l have to go.

07:29.199 --> 07:31.326
Please clean the bones,
Ms. Wick.

07:34.788 --> 07:36.528
But he said he was going.
Ha! Okay.

07:36.624 --> 07:40.162
How many times has he told us
that he has found a place,
and then something happens?

07:40.294 --> 07:43.127
Um, three.
Three, exactly.
It never happens.

07:43.213 --> 07:45.875
Which means we have
to make him leave.

07:45.966 --> 07:47.627
But I just said
that we liked him.

07:47.760 --> 07:51.378
We do. That’s why we have
to push him out of the nest.
Like Turo’us migrator/us .7

07:51.472 --> 07:53.588
No, like a bird, not a turd.
Don’t call him a turd.

07:53.682 --> 07:58.346
Well, Turo’us ml'grator/us
is the scientific name
for the robin, which is a bird.

07:58.437 --> 08:01.474
The point is, when he says
it didn’t work out,
we have to help him leave.

08:01.565 --> 08:03.521
- It’s for his own sake.
— [ Sweets ] Hey.

08:03.609 --> 08:05.565
Deanna Barbieri.

08:05.653 --> 08:08.269
Thirty—five, former sergeant
in the marines.

08:08.405 --> 08:12.364
She was given administrative discharge
12 months ago after a fistfight
with another marine.

08:12.451 --> 08:15.784
All of it’s part of a pattern of misconduct,
including assaulting an officer.

08:19.291 --> 08:20.997
[ Exhales ]

08:21.085 --> 08:23.076
— What?
- Oh. Booth and l...

08:23.170 --> 08:26.287
were just sitting here...

08:26.382 --> 08:29.419
in the diner,
looking at the menu,

08:29.510 --> 08:33.628
and, well, we got to wondering,
you know, how it went.

08:33.722 --> 08:36.099
— How what went?
- Your new place.

08:36.183 --> 08:37.923
Oh, great. I’m in.

08:38.018 --> 08:40.760
It’s perfect.
I’ll be out within a day.

08:40.854 --> 08:42.435
Is that okay?

08:42.523 --> 08:45.765
That’s great.
No complaints here.
Hey, I get my tub back.

08:45.859 --> 08:50.398
So, I think the first thing we
should do is talk to this marine
that our victim fought with.

08:50.531 --> 08:53.989
They were both kicked out
of the marines.
Mm—hmm.

08:54.076 --> 08:55.816
Her name’s Carlene Blayney.

08:55.911 --> 08:58.823
You know what. I’ll talk to her
this afternoon.

08:58.914 --> 09:00.950
Okay.

09:01.041 --> 09:04.784
— You’re not gonna stay for lunch?
- No. l have a lot to do, so—

09:04.920 --> 09:08.458
Bye.
lguess
he’s really leaving.

09:08.549 --> 09:10.085
[ Scoffs ]
Yeah, we’ll see.

09:13.846 --> 09:15.336
[ Daisy]
What are we making?

09:15.431 --> 09:17.638
Well, a swab from
the victim’s chest...

09:17.725 --> 09:19.636
revealed a mixture of
phosphorus and magnesium,

09:19.727 --> 09:24.346
an explosive used
in a certain kind of shell
called dragon’s breath.

09:24.481 --> 09:26.472
When fired, it produces
a 50—foot flame—
[ Clacking ]

09:26.567 --> 09:29.274
that lasts
for about three seconds.

09:29.361 --> 09:32.478
That would mean that the same
shot that killed the victim
also started the fire.

09:32.573 --> 09:36.282
Yeah, if it works,
which is what we are
here to find out.

09:36.368 --> 09:40.031
Oh, no, no, no.
What— Really?

09:45.627 --> 09:47.413
[Shotgun Cocks]

09:48.464 --> 09:50.204
Fire in the—

09:52.384 --> 09:53.885
...hole.

09:53.969 --> 09:56.881
Sorry. The trigger was
a little more sensitive
than I thought.

09:59.975 --> 10:01.431
What does that prove?

10:01.518 --> 10:03.804
The shot that killed the victim
also started the fire.

10:07.107 --> 10:10.315
[ Saroyan ]
Okay, now put it out.

10:11.779 --> 10:13.394
[Woman ]
Deanna and l
were actually friends.

10:13.489 --> 10:15.275
We went through
basic training together.

10:15.365 --> 10:19.404
She was a real soldier.
Deanna was the real deal.

10:19.495 --> 10:23.363
- Right, so what happened?
— She started talking about
the end of the world.

10:27.169 --> 10:29.376
She took
a swing at me.
So you laid her out.

10:29.463 --> 10:31.044
And then we both
got discharged.

10:31.131 --> 10:33.747
Deanna was pretty sure
that our whole society...

10:33.842 --> 10:35.958
was going to fall apart,
including the military.

10:36.094 --> 10:38.801
But you don’t believe that
society then will fall apart?
Nope.

10:38.889 --> 10:42.097
People are resilient.
We’re gonna be okay.

10:42.184 --> 10:44.300
Well, we have phone records
showing that you called her...

10:44.394 --> 10:46.055
eight times
in the last few months.

10:46.146 --> 10:49.013
Because I didn’t know
where she lived anymore.

10:49.107 --> 10:50.938
She disappeared.
Fell right off the grid.

10:51.026 --> 10:54.985
That’s a lot of concern
for someone who ruined
your career in the military.

10:56.031 --> 10:58.192
You never had
a fight with someone?

10:59.409 --> 11:02.151
You don’t find a lot
of friends in this world.

11:02.246 --> 11:05.113
l was trying to hang on
to one of mine.

11:05.207 --> 11:06.913
So she didn’t call you back?

11:10.254 --> 11:14.122
Look, I didn’t kill her.
I’m sorry she’s dead.

11:14.216 --> 11:17.083
I wish I had the chance
to tell her I’m sorry.

11:17.177 --> 11:18.792
Well, we found a shotgun
in your apartment.

11:18.887 --> 11:21.674
— We’re gonna run some tests on it.
— You do what you gotta do.

11:21.765 --> 11:26.054
Listen, I can’t— I can’t tell
if you killed her or not,
but in case you didn’t,

11:26.144 --> 11:29.011
I’d like to point out
that if you called her
eight times,

11:29.106 --> 11:30.767
she knew you were
trying to make up.

11:32.234 --> 11:34.270
Thank you for that.

11:35.863 --> 11:38.070
Thank you.

11:41.577 --> 11:43.568
[ Device Beeps ]

11:45.831 --> 11:49.699
You found something,
Ms. Wick?
I did. Look at this.

11:49.793 --> 11:54.332
When I was cleaning the femur,
I found a remodeled injury,
less than a year old.

11:54.423 --> 11:56.414
Very good work,
Ms. Wick.

11:56.508 --> 11:59.671
This is a nasty injury.
Expertly set.

11:59.803 --> 12:03.466
But the cause—
It’s not familiar to me.
I thought you might have a theory.

12:03.557 --> 12:05.422
l have seen breaks
like this before.

12:05.517 --> 12:08.429
The remodeled splintering
indicates that she was hit...

12:08.520 --> 12:11.011
with something
of a relatively high density...

12:11.106 --> 12:13.347
— at a relatively high speed.
- A bullet?

12:13.442 --> 12:15.899
More dense
and slower than a bullet.

12:15.986 --> 12:18.147
A baseball bat.
A car bumper.

12:18.238 --> 12:20.695
Faster than both
and more localized.

12:23.869 --> 12:28.613
Remodeling shows striations
from the splintering.

12:28.707 --> 12:30.197
The Civil War.

12:31.418 --> 12:35.002
Hobbyists still use
Civil War munitions.
Oh!

12:36.590 --> 12:38.751
A musket ball.
Larger.

12:38.842 --> 12:41.458
I believe we’re looking at
an injury from a cannonball.

12:42.846 --> 12:46.680
We have the medical records
from the Veterans Administration.

12:46.767 --> 12:48.348
There’s no mention of a wound.

12:48.435 --> 12:51.222
How does someone
who lives off the grid
get shot by a cannon...

12:51.313 --> 12:53.349
and get medical attention
this good?

13:03.700 --> 13:06.316
[ Hodgins ]
I took samples of
the victim’s remodeled femur.

13:06.411 --> 13:08.948
The injury contained
cast iron and lead.

13:09.039 --> 13:10.620
[ Daisy]
Who makes
her own cannonballs?

13:10.707 --> 13:14.291
Well, she had
this old Civil War
cannonball press,

13:14.378 --> 13:16.334
which requires
cast iron and lead—

13:16.421 --> 13:20.164
no brass, copper or steel
that would be used today—
so she did.

13:20.258 --> 13:22.590
So she shot herself
in the leg with a cannon?

13:22.678 --> 13:25.920
Are you thinking some
terribly complicated
suicide attempt?

13:26.014 --> 13:28.847
I’m thinking accident,
but I like your flair
for the dramatic.

13:28.934 --> 13:34.270
I’ll be testing my theory later
when | find a matching cannon
from the Civil War exhibit.

13:34.356 --> 13:37.723
You won’t have to.
l matched the wound
on the victim’s femur.

13:37.818 --> 13:39.979
You said the diameter
of a two—pounder cannonball...

13:40.112 --> 13:42.569
was 6.8 centimeters,
right?
Yeah.

13:44.241 --> 13:47.904
Guess you heard that Sweets
is finally moving out
of Mom and Dad’s house.

13:47.995 --> 13:50.236
You misjudge Lance.
He’s not a child.

13:50.330 --> 13:53.367
He’s responsible
for managing pro bono
psychological counseling...

13:53.458 --> 13:55.244
at the homeless shelter
in Penn Quarter,

13:55.335 --> 13:57.997
and he helped me make
investments in my 401 (k)
that withstood the crash.

13:58.088 --> 14:00.204
So his only problem
is sleeping alone?

14:00.298 --> 14:03.711
Nobody likes that, Dr. Hodgins.
Isn’t that why you married
Ms. Montenegro?

14:03.802 --> 14:05.588
[ Chuckles ]
Ooh, snap.

14:05.679 --> 14:08.136
Okay, the diameter
of the ball...

14:08.223 --> 14:10.464
matches the outline
of the break on her leg...

14:10.559 --> 14:13.392
as well as the directionality
of the splintering.

14:13.478 --> 14:15.093
Very impressive,
Ms. Montenegro.

14:15.230 --> 14:17.346
Thanks, Daisy.
Well, l-l’d like
to be sure.

14:17.441 --> 14:21.104
We should definitely check velocity
as well as density of the ball—

14:21.194 --> 14:22.980
I know what this is about.
You just want to—

14:23.071 --> 14:25.153
Yes, | just
want to be thorough.

14:25.240 --> 14:27.026
So if you need me,

14:27.117 --> 14:29.324
I’ll be next door
in the Antietam exhibit.

14:34.166 --> 14:35.781
- A cannonball?
— Yeah, that’s what they think.

14:35.876 --> 14:38.083
It’s all very old school, you know?
She makes her own ammo.

14:38.211 --> 14:40.202
But a cannon?
Yeah, a cannon.

14:40.297 --> 14:44.040
She— She’s probably making, you know,
ammo for other people as well.

14:44.134 --> 14:46.671
So if we find out
who those people are,
we might find our killer.

14:46.762 --> 14:49.504
lt’s the only lead that we have.
Plus the test on
Carlene Blayney’s shotgun—

14:49.639 --> 14:51.254
that came back
negative as well.
[Cell Phone Rings]

14:51.349 --> 14:52.850
Oh, sorry. Hold on.

14:52.934 --> 14:56.301
Sweets here.
Yes! Thank you.

14:56.396 --> 14:58.637
I’d like a quote
on renter’s insurance.

14:58.732 --> 15:03.021
Sure, I’ll e—mail you
all my information and
an itemized list of valuables.

15:03.111 --> 15:04.692
Great. Thanks. Bye.

15:04.780 --> 15:07.237
Sorry.
Ah, it’s okay.

15:07.324 --> 15:09.235
You’re all good with the move?
You need any help?

15:09.367 --> 15:12.154
No, but thanks.
All right.

15:12.245 --> 15:14.201
You’re sure you checked
that building out
for asbestos...

15:14.331 --> 15:16.913
and plumbing leaks,
cracks in the foundation—
Yeah.

15:17.042 --> 15:18.828
So everything’s good?
Yeah. All done.

15:18.919 --> 15:21.706
’Cause I don’t wanna hear
any crazy excuses from you
that you gotta move back in.

15:21.797 --> 15:23.253
Not gonna happen.
l’m set.

15:23.340 --> 15:25.706
You’re okay living
in a building
full of shrinks?

15:25.801 --> 15:27.507
Hey, we have
a lot in common,

15:27.594 --> 15:29.710
plus we have the skills
to work out our disagreements...

15:29.805 --> 15:31.261
in a healthy and constructive manner.

15:31.348 --> 15:33.430
But I’m gonna miss you too,
Agent Booth.

15:33.517 --> 15:38.477
Right. Yeah. Well, | see you
all the time here at work.
Plus, | get my tub back,

15:38.563 --> 15:41.054
and I won’t have to look at
that stupid pomegranate juice
in my refrigerator.

15:41.191 --> 15:43.352
You still haven’t
tried it yet?
No, I haven’t, okay?

15:43.443 --> 15:45.604
— That’s called “shrinkjuice.”
— It’s just pomegranate juice.

15:45.737 --> 15:49.355
Why don’t you gather all your
new neighbors together, and you
can have a shrinkjuice party?

15:49.491 --> 15:52.198
It’s good.
Yeah, sure.
Enjoy that!

15:54.996 --> 15:57.408
There’s pitting
in the mandible and maxilla.

15:57.499 --> 15:59.706
I assumed
it was from buckshot
when she was killed,

15:59.793 --> 16:02.034
but the damage is too small
and not deep enough.

16:02.129 --> 16:05.963
Mmm. Dr. Hodgins said
there was no buckshot
in the shell.

16:06.049 --> 16:07.835
We already know
she was making
cannonballs.

16:07.926 --> 16:10.133
Maybe there’s another
form of ammunition
we’re overlooking?

16:10.220 --> 16:15.385
Look again, Ms. Wick.
This pitting was not caused
by external forces.

16:15.517 --> 16:20.056
Caries sicca.
Caused by the gummatous
lesions of syphilis.

16:20.147 --> 16:23.105
- Syphilis?
- The victim was in the latent
stage of the disease.

16:23.191 --> 16:27.480
- I should have caught that.
— The disease is not as common
as it once was, fortunately.

16:27.571 --> 16:29.937
— Safe sex, yes.
— l was thinking of penicillin.

16:30.031 --> 16:34.650
I clearly have less faith
in the sexual restraint
of the masses than you do.

16:34.744 --> 16:37.907
There was no mention of syphilis
on the victim’s medical records.

16:37.998 --> 16:39.488
She may not have known
she had it.

16:39.583 --> 16:43.451
That disease
can lie dormant for years
before any symptoms appear.

16:43.545 --> 16:45.456
This could explain
the victim’s hostility.

16:45.589 --> 16:49.878
Her tissue samples showed
benzodiazepine in her system.
She’d taken a sedative?

16:49.968 --> 16:52.755
There was no mention
of her being on
any prescribed medication.

16:52.846 --> 16:54.882
She wouldn’t be the first one
to take drugs illegally.

16:58.518 --> 17:00.759
[Angela ]
Hodgins said the cannonballs
were made with lead,

17:00.854 --> 17:03.186
so I did a search
for anyone near
the victim...

17:03.273 --> 17:06.606
who was buying up
large quantities of lead
from salvage yards.

17:07.777 --> 17:09.358
Dr. Fred Dumaski.

17:09.446 --> 17:11.027
Yeah, it’s a family practitioner.

17:11.114 --> 17:13.651
Who gave up his practice.

17:13.742 --> 17:16.358
Maybe he was done
with the whole
“do no harm” thing.

17:16.453 --> 17:18.569
[Angela ]
This is not necessary, Hodgins.

17:18.663 --> 17:20.494
I already double—checked
the figures.

17:20.582 --> 17:22.538
A cannonball fractured
our victim’s leg.

17:22.626 --> 17:24.708
And I am not doubting that,
Angie.

17:24.794 --> 17:26.876
Then why exactly
are you doing this?

17:26.963 --> 17:29.921
Have we all forgot the concept
of the double—blind study?

17:30.008 --> 17:34.377
— Doesn’t apply to artillery.
- Theories are improved
as more evidence is gathered,

17:34.471 --> 17:37.087
so that accuracy in prediction
improves over time.

17:37.182 --> 17:40.424
For that, we need independent
strands of evidence, rather than
a single foundational source.

17:40.518 --> 17:42.099
And you cannot argue with that.

17:42.187 --> 17:43.643
So, he’s never shot a cannon.

17:43.730 --> 17:46.472
Excuse me for loving my work.

17:46.566 --> 17:48.522
Goggles and ear protection,
please.

17:50.028 --> 17:52.314
— I made the cannonball myself.
— Very impressive.

17:52.405 --> 17:54.612
Replicated it exactly.
They used a lot of lead.

17:54.699 --> 17:57.281
— Already on it.
— Right. Okay.

17:57.369 --> 17:58.859
Ready?

18:00.163 --> 18:02.154
Okay, everyone, stand back!

18:04.292 --> 18:06.704
Fire in the hole!

18:21.309 --> 18:23.300
Whoa!

18:27.649 --> 18:30.231
So, velocity is—

18:30.318 --> 18:31.979
[With Hodgins]
1,400 feet per second.

18:32.070 --> 18:34.231
...per... second.

18:34.322 --> 18:35.402
Okay, right.

18:35.490 --> 18:39.403
Now, range at five degrees
would be—

18:39.494 --> 18:41.200
— 1,600 yards.
- ...yards.

18:41.288 --> 18:43.620
Okay, good. So then,
we have corroboration,

18:43.707 --> 18:45.447
which is exactly
what we want as scientists.

18:45.542 --> 18:47.248
Of course.
Now clean up this mess.

18:47.335 --> 18:48.450
— One more?
— No.

18:48.545 --> 18:49.625
— It’s all setup.
— No.

18:49.754 --> 18:51.255
I made another
cannonbau
No.

18:51.339 --> 18:53.295
[ Stammers ]

18:53.383 --> 18:55.590
I’ll send Booth the info
about the doctor.

18:55.719 --> 18:57.630
[ Lowered Voice ]
That was actually awesome.
Totally.

18:57.721 --> 18:59.211
He must never know.

19:04.227 --> 19:06.218
[ Chuckles ]

19:08.565 --> 19:10.226
He’s a doctor who makes
cannonballs?
[ Booth ] Yeah.

19:10.317 --> 19:13.980
Fred Dumaski.
But he goes by the name
of Dr. Apocalypse.

19:14.070 --> 19:15.901
Oh, all right.
He’s a survivalist.

19:15.989 --> 19:19.152
Yeah, they call themselves
the Doomsday Preppers.

19:19.242 --> 19:22.154
[ Sweets ] “The Preppers’
Guide to Canning Foods.”
“Do-lt-Yourself Doctoring.”

19:22.245 --> 19:24.281
“Weapons for a Wasted World”?

19:24.372 --> 19:27.205
Check out this video
on how to make cannonballs.

19:27.292 --> 19:30.784
Global events such as a nuclear
attack by terror/sts,

19:30.879 --> 19:34.121
or more l/ke/y, an econom/c collapse,
are lne wtab/e.

19:34.215 --> 19:37.378
Preparing to survive
such an event is simple logic.

19:37.469 --> 19:41.132
And making your own
ammunition for weapons
s/mp/e to maintain...

19:41.222 --> 19:44.760
— /S a basic skill that you must ha ve.
- Okay. Wack job.

19:44.851 --> 19:47.843
There are complex psychological factors
that go into a person’s life choices.

19:47.937 --> 19:50.974
- To dismiss it with an easy
moniker like that—
- Really?

19:51.107 --> 19:53.314
In this case,
I’m fine with “wack jobs.”
Complete wack job.

19:53.401 --> 19:55.141
Is there any evidence
that he knew Deanna Barbieri?

19:55.236 --> 19:58.603
Well, being a survivalist explains
why she was living in a shed.

19:58.698 --> 20:01.906
These people, these wack jobs—
They’re a tight—knit community.

20:01.993 --> 20:04.405
They’re fiercely defensive,
and they’re suspicious
of the government.

20:04.496 --> 20:07.829
I— It won’t be easy
to get Dr. Apocalypse to talk.

20:07.916 --> 20:10.703
Well, a neighbor says that
he hasn’t been back to his place
since Deanna died.

20:10.835 --> 20:13.668
That should be enough
to get a warrant.
Oh, it was, yeah.

20:13.755 --> 20:17.873
We searched his house and found out
that he bought land last October.

20:17.967 --> 20:20.800
Ten acres of nothing
in Wise County, Virginia.

20:22.972 --> 20:25.964
He spent half a million dollars
on 10 acres of nothing?

20:26.059 --> 20:27.890
The land itself only
cost $50,000,

20:27.977 --> 20:31.686
but the rest
went to a company
called Safe Harbors.

20:31.773 --> 20:34.310
They specialize
in survival bunkers.

20:34.401 --> 20:38.235
So you got ammo,
you got survivalists
in a military—grade bunker.

20:38.321 --> 20:39.777
No, this is not good.

20:39.864 --> 20:42.446
Time to smoke out
the wack jobs.

20:46.496 --> 20:50.114
[ Booth ] Stay in teams.
Watch out for booby traps.
[Agent] Copy that.

20:50.208 --> 20:52.073
Looking for an area
where you can
bury a bunker.

20:52.168 --> 20:54.159
[Agent #2 ]
Watch your 6:00.

20:59.926 --> 21:03.339
I got it.
Twenty yards, 11:00.

21:04.305 --> 21:06.216
Move, move.
Move out.

21:07.142 --> 21:08.723
Hold it.
Nobody move.

21:08.810 --> 21:10.346
[Agent]
Stand down.

21:10.437 --> 21:13.144
[Agent #2 ]
lt’s connected to
an explosive device, sir.

21:14.441 --> 21:16.352
[Agent #1 ]
Clear.

21:22.490 --> 21:24.401
- Wire’s secure.
— The suspect...

21:24.492 --> 21:26.278
and whoever else is down there
could be heavily armed.

21:26.369 --> 21:27.870
Move. Move!

21:34.711 --> 21:37.748
- [ Agent #2 ]
It has a time lock on it.
— Gonna have to blow it.

21:45.013 --> 21:47.345
Get 10 yards back.

21:47.432 --> 21:49.468
[Agent#1 ]
Ten—yard perimeter
around the bunker.

21:51.060 --> 21:52.641
Let’s keep
the weapons trained.

21:52.729 --> 21:55.220
— We don’t know what the hell’s
gonna come out of there.
— Yes, sir.

21:56.816 --> 21:59.193
— Clear.
— Clear.

21:59.277 --> 22:01.268
[Agent #1 ]
Smoke ’em.

22:10.914 --> 22:12.620
[ Bleats ]

22:12.707 --> 22:14.823
- [ Bleats ]
— [ Squawks ]

22:14.918 --> 22:17.625
[ Clucking ]

22:19.255 --> 22:21.086
[Man Coughing]
l’m unarmed.

22:21.216 --> 22:23.707
Hold your fire.
[ Booth ]
Hands on your head.

22:23.843 --> 22:25.834
On the ground. Down.
[ Man ]
I’ve got a bad back.

22:25.929 --> 22:28.170
[Agent #2 ]
Hands on your head. Let’s go.
On your knees! Move!

22:28.264 --> 22:30.550
— [ Booth ]
Get on the ground. Over!
— [ People Coughing]

22:30.683 --> 22:32.423
[Agent #1 ] Move!
[Man]
Hold your fire!

22:32.519 --> 22:34.009
[Agent #2 ]
On the ground!

22:34.103 --> 22:35.968
- l’m Dr. Apocalypse!
— On your knees!

22:36.064 --> 22:38.055
I can explain everything!

22:39.901 --> 22:42.062
I can explain everything.
[Agent #2 ]
Get down!

22:48.034 --> 22:49.615
[Man Coughing]

22:54.958 --> 22:58.576
I met Deanna online. I could
tell right away that she’d be
a huge asset to the group.

22:58.711 --> 23:02.044
[ Booth ]
You mean weaponry?
Weapons, defensive tactics,

23:02.131 --> 23:04.713
ammunition, her military training.

23:04.801 --> 23:06.337
But also just her character.

23:06.469 --> 23:09.336
Okay, when you say “our group”?
We’re preppers,
Agent Booth.

23:09.430 --> 23:11.842
We’re ready for
the impending collapse of society.

23:11.933 --> 23:13.889
What’s gonna cause
the collapse of society?

23:13.977 --> 23:17.890
The economy, race wars,
ecological disasters,
global climate change,

23:17.981 --> 23:20.347
terrorist attack, viral pandemic—
take your pick.

23:20.441 --> 23:22.272
— lt’s inevitable.
— Right, okay.

23:22.360 --> 23:24.191
How did Deanna
break her leg?

23:24.279 --> 23:27.612
I’m guessing that showed up
in her autopsy report.

23:27.699 --> 23:30.566
It’s odd that there’s no mention
of it in her medical records.

23:30.660 --> 23:34.528
It was an accident.
I was practicing loading
the cannon, and it went off.

23:34.622 --> 23:37.910
Deanna and I saw it
as a perfect opportunity...

23:38.001 --> 23:41.789
to show that we could be self—sufficient
in terms of trauma care.

23:41.879 --> 23:43.961
Her accident actually
pulled our group together.

23:44.048 --> 23:46.334
What were you hiding from
when we found you?

23:46.426 --> 23:49.589
Nothing. It was a practice drill.
We knew we were
going in for a week.

23:49.679 --> 23:51.169
What happened to your arm?

23:54.183 --> 23:55.468
Ouch.

23:55.560 --> 23:58.222
- I gave myself a shot.
- Trauma care.

23:58.354 --> 24:00.185
[ Sweets ]
For what?
Venereal disease.

24:01.608 --> 24:03.644
Our victim had syphilis.
You have a venereal disease.

24:03.735 --> 24:06.067
Self—treated. Maybe you can get away
without your wife finding out.

24:06.195 --> 24:11.235
The world as you know it is
about to end. Delores knew
everything about me and Deanna.

24:11.326 --> 24:12.782
It’s a new world.

24:12.869 --> 24:14.780
Not yet, Dr. Apocalypse, all right?

24:14.871 --> 24:17.658
You’re still practicing, okay?
This is still the same old world.

24:22.962 --> 24:25.419
[Hodgins]
I got this list of items
in the bunker from the FBI.

24:25.506 --> 24:27.633
Well, the preppers
were very well equipped.

24:27.717 --> 24:31.881
I suspect they
could’ve survived down there
for months quite successfully.

24:31.971 --> 24:34.963
Thank God I am a conspiracy theorist
and not a doomsday hysteric.

24:35.058 --> 24:39.142
Well, it’s not hysteria.
In the long run, human beings
are scheduled for extinction.

24:39.228 --> 24:42.470
Yeah, when the sun
expands into a red giant
in three billion years.

24:42.607 --> 24:46.600
Not necessarily. We already have
enough weapons to annihilate
all life on the planet.

24:46.694 --> 24:50.437
You have tremendous faith
in a violent species
such as ours...

24:50.531 --> 24:52.817
to think that we will
have the self—control
not to use them.

24:52.909 --> 24:55.070
Man, I came to you
with good news.
Now I’m just depressed.

24:55.203 --> 24:59.071
I want good news.
Well, phosphorus and magnesium
were on the FBI. list.

24:59.207 --> 25:01.698
So?
So I found both of them
on the victim.

25:01.793 --> 25:03.829
And they were the source
of the fire.

25:03.920 --> 25:06.707
Which means one of the preppers
is probably the killer.

25:10.301 --> 25:14.260
Delores Dumaski,
Mrs. Apocalypse.
The one he cheated on.

25:14.347 --> 25:18.386
Yeah, she specializes in nutrition,
food prep and storage.

25:18.476 --> 25:22.389
Now, Dennis Bukovac
is a retired minister.

25:22.480 --> 25:25.938
He’s in charge of the group’s
emotional and spiritual health.

25:26.067 --> 25:28.979
Right. I wonder what the minister
thinks of free sex.
Right.

25:29.070 --> 25:30.560
Milo Mills, 28.

25:30.655 --> 25:32.361
He’s got a degree
in mechanical engineering.

25:32.448 --> 25:36.032
- The one who fixes everything.
— Yeah. Generators, ventilation, lighting.

25:36.119 --> 25:37.780
Maybe he worked weapons
with the victim.

25:38.996 --> 25:40.577
Any of these people
crazy enough to kill?

25:40.665 --> 25:42.451
Wack jobs— all of ’em.

25:43.626 --> 25:44.661
Yeah.

25:48.131 --> 25:51.339
[Angela ]
So I was able to identify a few
of the objects from the fire.

25:51.426 --> 25:52.882
Awesome, Angie.

25:52.969 --> 25:55.961
You literally recovered
evidence from the ashes.

25:56.055 --> 25:58.967
So this pile of debris here
is a cot.

25:59.058 --> 26:02.095
— Okay. What’s that lump there?
— That is a screwdriver.

26:02.186 --> 26:04.643
This is like a treasure hunt.
What’s that?

26:04.731 --> 26:07.017
— That used to be a tool box.
- Okay.

26:07.108 --> 26:09.440
I recognize this.
This is a shell casing.

26:09.569 --> 26:12.402
But what’s that?
It’s a jar of nails.

26:12.488 --> 26:14.649
Now, under this plate here,

26:14.741 --> 26:18.484
there’s this singed paper,
which I think is a letter.

26:18.578 --> 26:22.070
I’m gonna try to get it from
evidence and see if we can
figure out what it is.

26:24.917 --> 26:29.035
Hey, are you listening to your lovely
and very clever wife over here?

26:29.130 --> 26:32.122
Yeah. No, sorry.
It’s just this—this screwdriver...

26:32.216 --> 26:37.586
would’ve been made out of
beryllium, which has a melting
point of 865 degrees Celsius.

26:37.722 --> 26:39.713
Okay.
But...

26:39.807 --> 26:42.594
the shell casing
is made of yellow brass.

26:42.685 --> 26:44.141
Well, why didn’t it melt?

26:44.228 --> 26:48.141
Yellow brass has a melting point
of 905 degrees Celsius.

26:48.232 --> 26:52.646
So the temperature
was greater than
865 degrees...

26:52.737 --> 26:55.945
but less than
905 degrees.

26:56.032 --> 26:57.488
So... what?

26:57.575 --> 26:59.736
Angie, at these temperatures,
a human body would’ve been...

26:59.827 --> 27:02.569
completely reduced to ash
in three hours.

27:02.663 --> 27:05.279
So either the temperature
of the fire wasn’t that hot...

27:05.374 --> 27:07.751
or it burned for a much
shorter period of time.

27:07.835 --> 27:09.746
Yeah,
about half the time.

27:09.837 --> 27:12.374
l’m not gonna be insulted
if you run a simulation
and check my math—

27:12.465 --> 27:15.582
Oh, I will.
But if you’re right,

27:15.676 --> 27:19.840
then the fire started
somewhere closer to 8:30
and not 7:00.

27:19.931 --> 27:21.296
Yeah.

27:21.390 --> 27:25.053
Meaning no one in that
bunker could’ve murdered
Deanna Barbieri.

27:29.732 --> 27:32.519
So you’re absolutely sure
that nobody in that bunker...

27:32.610 --> 27:34.316
could’ve killed Deanna Barbieri?

27:34.403 --> 27:37.315
Why do you keep asking me
to qualify my conclusions?

27:37.406 --> 27:39.943
You know that l,
as well as the others
on my team, are brilliant.

27:40.034 --> 27:43.868
It’s just that survivalists
are a close—knit group.
They’re like the military.

27:43.955 --> 27:46.241
Deanna was outspoken.
She challenged authority.

27:46.332 --> 27:49.665
Somebody like that would
challenge the very essence
of the group dynamic.

27:49.752 --> 27:52.664
And killing her would be
a logical extension
of the needs of the group.

27:52.755 --> 27:56.293
— Yes.
— It doesn’t seem to be
anyone from that group.

27:56.384 --> 27:58.841
But Deanna lived off the grid.

27:58.928 --> 28:00.839
Even Carlene Blayney
didn’t know how to find her.

28:00.930 --> 28:03.797
She wasn’t in contact
with anyone except that group.

28:03.891 --> 28:07.509
I’m sorry, Lance.
You’re gonna have to come up
with another theory.

28:07.603 --> 28:10.845
The condition of the burned
bones combined with
the temperature of the fire...

28:10.940 --> 28:14.603
tells us that the body
burned for a maximum
of 90 minutes.

28:14.694 --> 28:16.480
Okay, well, that proves...

28:16.571 --> 28:19.734
that Deanna was killed
at around 8:30 am, not 7:00.

28:19.824 --> 28:23.191
But all the preppers
were already locked
in the bunker by then.

28:23.286 --> 28:24.776
You’re wonderful, Lance.

28:26.330 --> 28:27.319
Excuse me?

28:28.791 --> 28:33.660
You’re so... thoughtful
and committed to the truth.

28:33.754 --> 28:35.585
It’s a rare quality.

28:35.673 --> 28:37.959
Even in the way
you approached
getting your own place.

28:39.760 --> 28:42.251
— Okay. Okay, I get it.
- What?

28:42.346 --> 28:45.884
You think that l was acting
like a child by living
with Booth and Dr. Brennan.

28:45.975 --> 28:47.636
Not at all.

28:47.727 --> 28:52.391
I thought it showed
great maturity and strength.

28:52.481 --> 28:54.392
Everyone was gonna judge you
for being weak,

28:54.483 --> 28:58.317
but you knew that you needed
time and a safe place
to collect yourself,

28:58.404 --> 29:00.736
reflect on
what happened.

29:00.823 --> 29:03.189
Where better to do that
than with people
who love you?

29:04.535 --> 29:08.995
Any person who can’t accept
that— that’s the weak person.

29:12.835 --> 29:15.952
I think you’re pretty
wonderful yourself, Daisy.

29:16.672 --> 29:18.663
I know.

29:18.758 --> 29:21.215
Makes no sense
that we couldn’t
make a go of it.

29:22.011 --> 29:23.501
None.

29:25.222 --> 29:27.508
Maybe somebody tampered
with the time lock.

29:27.600 --> 29:29.431
Hodgins says
that’s impossible.

29:29.518 --> 29:33.852
Any tampering with mechanisms
sets off an alarm and makes it
impossible to reset the lock.

29:33.940 --> 29:35.771
- It was locked
when they arrived.
— [ Groans ]

29:35.858 --> 29:38.895
Well, there’s gotta be some other way
in and out of that bunker.

29:38.986 --> 29:42.820
The killer could’ve snuck out,
killed Deanna, snuck back in.

29:42.907 --> 29:45.944
